Paper summary\
-------------\
The paper proposes an agent-based modelling framework to forecast electricity market behaviour. It improves upon an existing framework, viz. Elecsim, to sufficiently capture contributions from coal, gas, nuclear, renewables and other similar sources.\
\
The paper provides a comprehensive framework that considers prediction of electricity generation in the future, by detailing the contributions and behaviour of different sources of generation. Comparisons were against real data of 2018, and BEIS data from 2018-2035. Reasons for variation in generation over different time periods were also explained.\
\
Reasons to accept the paper (2-3 sentences)\
-------------------------------------------\
The paper provides a through evaluation on actual UK electricity generation data for the year 2018, and BEIS data from 2018-2035. It demonstrates the impact of coal, gas, oil, nuclear and renewables on the total electricity generation. The paper also considers the minimal representative days which improves the accuracy of prediction. Accuracy of the results is validated using different error metrics. The paper also provides comprehensive analysis of the results; it details the reason for changes in electricity generation.\
\
Main weaknesses of the paper (2-3 sentences)\
--------------------------------------------\
The authors train on data from 2013-2017, and then validate on 2018. Data from 2018-2035 is the expected behaviour according to BEIS. So realistically, actual data of only 2018 is present. If the results were also validated against actual data of 2019 or even 2017, only then the comparisons against BEIS data till 2035 will look convincing.\
\
The authors have not justified the value of parameters considered. For example, in second para Section 5.3, 60 scenarios were considered without providing any details; in Sections 4.4.1/2, how the values for m and c were selected in not specified.\
