Paper summary\
-------------\
The paper presents a validation study for the electricity market model ElecSim applied to the UK electricity system. It expands the model using representative days approximating the full time series for electricity demand and onshore, offshore, solar capacity factors. Using genetic algorithm based optimization, the prediced price duration curve used by the model is parameterized to model the transtion from coal to gas in the UK between 2013 and 2018, and a future scenario to 2035.\
\
Reasons to accept the paper (2-3 sentences)\
-------------------------------------------\
Modelling electricity markets using agent based or simulation models is a topic of wide interest. Validation of such models against historic scenarios or results from other studies can yield valuable insights about the accuracy and limitations of the models. The paper is well written, giving a good background about the electricity market models, and a detailed presentation of the results.\
\
Main weaknesses of the paper (2-3 sentences)\
--------------------------------------------\
The study presented in the paper builds on the framework ElecSim, but unfortunately, this model is not described sufficiently in the paper. Accordingly it is very difficult to assess the improvements of the model due to the representative days, and the role of the optimized predicted price duration curve. While the overall presentation is often very detailed, some relevant definitions are not given in detail or remain unclear.\
\
Detailed comments on the paper\
------------------------------\
Some minor comments:\
- The Predicted Price Duration Curve and also other duration curves should be defined clearly.\
- The price duration curve was modelled linearly, is this a limiting factor?\
- The genetic algorithms for doing the optimization have been briefly motivated, but since this a central method of the study, more discussions or studies would have been interesting.\
\
- There is a typo in Equation 1, $t$ should be replaced by $i$\
- Equation 2 should be checked - why is there a summation over $t$? What is the index $m$? Why are the capital costs included?\
- There are typos in Equation 4, in the $\\min$ the first $m$ should be replaced by $m_y$, and the second $m$ should be replaced by $c_y$.\
- The explanation of the procedure from Equation 7 to Equation 9 should be clarified.\
- In Equations 10 and 11 it is unclear why the duration curves are used, and not the actual and approximated time series.\
- Are references [32] and [33] the same?}